   "source": [
    "# Parameters and Their Optimisation\n",
    "\n",
    "In this chapter we will talk about what happens when you train your model, and what you can do if the optimisation process fails to find a good fit.\n",
    "\n",
    "As usual we start with some imports:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "34147a0a",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:37.783750Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:37.783582Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.567141Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.566583Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "from typing import Optional\n",
    "\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import pandas as pd\n",
    "import tensorflow as tf\n",
    "import tensorflow_probability as tfp\n",
    "from matplotlib.axes import Axes\n",
    "\n",
    "import gpflow\n",
    "from gpflow.experimental.check_shapes import check_shapes"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "44f14a2d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## The Module and Parameter classes"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "13febab1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The two fundamental classes of GPflow are [gpflow.Module](../../api/gpflow/index.html#gpflow-module) and [gpflow.Parameter](../../api/gpflow/index.html#gpflow-parameter). Parameters are leaf nodes holding numerical values, that can be tuned / trained to make the model fit the data. Modules recursively composes other modules and parameters to create models. All the GPflow models, kernels, mean functions, etc. are modules.\n",
    "\n",
    "As an example, let's build a simple linear model:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "63ba95fd",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.569623Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.569330Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.573693Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.573191Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class LinearModel(gpflow.Module):\n",
    "    @check_shapes(\n",
    "        \"slope: [n_inputs, n_outputs]\",\n",
    "        \"bias: [n_outputs]\",\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    def __init__(\n",
    "        self, slope: gpflow.base.TensorData, bias: gpflow.base.TensorData\n",
    "    ) -> None:\n",
    "        self.slope = gpflow.Parameter(slope)\n",
    "        self.bias = gpflow.Parameter(bias)\n",
    "\n",
    "    @check_shapes(\n",
    "        \"X: [n_rows, n_inputs]\",\n",
    "        \"return: [n_rows, n_outputs]\",\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    def predict(self, X: gpflow.base.TensorData) -> tf.Tensor:\n",
    "        return X @ self.slope + self.bias[:, None]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8d8607df",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice that in ``__init__`` we directly pass data to the parameters. The `Parameter` class takes many arguments (which we will discuss below), but it is reasonably intelligent as in: We can pass it \"raw\" numerical values with a Python list, a NumPy array, or a TensorFlow tensor; or we can pass it another `Parameter` and it will take values from that. Being able to pass a `Parameter` to ``__init__`` gives us a convenient way to configure the parameter in detail."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cde5048c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Inspecting parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's first create an instance of our `LinearModel`:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "b615b1d4",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {

     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.607317Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [

   "cell_type": "markdown",

   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Optimisation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "684275d2",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The objective of optimisation is to change the parameters so that your model fits the data. Generally an optimiser takes a \"loss\" function and a list of parameters, it then changes the parameters to minimise the loss function.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let's us try to optimise our `LinearModel`.\n",
    "\n",
    "First we need some data. This data is computed manually, given $y_i = 2x_{i0} + 3x_{i1} + 1$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "6e868877",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.672917Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.672767Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.675544Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.675053Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X_train = np.array([[0, 0], [0, 2], [1, 0], [3, 2]])\n",
    "Y_train = np.array([[1], [7], [3], [13]])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f513b3fa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next we need our loss function. A common choice is the mean squared error:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "e2b375d8",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.677418Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.677274Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.679932Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.679463Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def loss() -> tf.Tensor:\n",
    "    Y_predicted = model.predict(X_train)\n",
    "    squared_error = (Y_predicted - Y_train) ** 2\n",
    "    return tf.reduce_mean(squared_error)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "88c00f22",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Be aware that GPflow models come with a loss-function built in. Use `model.training_loss`. See our chapter on [Data Management](data_management.html) for more details."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5ef67bb0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now we can plug this into the default GPflow optimiser:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "e7d30afe",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.681811Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:40.681643Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.298094Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.297578Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<table>\n",
       "<thead>\n",
       "<tr><th>name             </th><th>class    </th><th>transform  </th><th>prior  </th><th>trainable  </th><th>shape  </th><th>dtype  </th><th>value  </th></tr>\n",
       "</thead>\n",
       "<tbody>\n",
       "<tr><td>LinearModel.slope</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Identity   </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>(2, 1) </td><td>float64</td><td>[[2.]\n",
       " [3.]]        </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>LinearModel.bias </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Identity   </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>(1,)   </td><td>float64</td><td>[1.]   </td></tr>\n",
       "</tbody>\n",
       "</table>"
      ],
      "text/plain": [
       "<IPython.core.display.HTML object>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "opt.minimize(loss, model.trainable_variables)\n",
    "gpflow.utilities.print_summary(model)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "336777f5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice how the optimiser recovered the slope of $(2, 3)$ and bias of $1$ from the equation we used to generate the data: $y_i = 2x_{i0} + 3x_{i1} + 1$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "429bff63",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## What to do if you models fails to fit\n",
    "\n",
    "In our above example the optimiser perfectly recovered the parameters of the process that generated our data. However, that was a very easy problem we were solving. As you start working with more complicated data sets models you may find that the optimiser fails to find a good fit for you model. In this section we will discuss what you can do to help it."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "39a16195",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Dataset: $CO_2$ levels\n",
    "\n",
    "As an example we will use a dataset of atmospheric $CO_2$ levels, as measured at the [Mauna Loa observatory](https://gml.noaa.gov/obop/mlo/) in Hawaii:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "b9adb28d",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.300233Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.300080Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.901078Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.898654Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "co2_data = pd.read_csv(\n",
    "    \"https://gml.noaa.gov/webdata/ccgg/trends/co2/co2_mm_mlo.csv\", comment=\"#\"\n",
    ")\n",
    "# co2_data = co2_data[co2_data[\"decimal date\"] > 1990]\n",
    "Xco2 = co2_data[\"decimal date\"].values[:, None]\n",
    "Yco2 = co2_data[\"average\"].values[:, None]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2726e3ff",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And we will define some helper functions to train and plot a model with the data:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "15410d8b",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.909046Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.908863Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.914390Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:41.913873Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_co2_model_prediction(\n",
    "    ax: Axes, model: gpflow.models.GPModel, start: float, stop: float\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    Xplot = np.linspace(start, stop, 200)[:, None]\n",
    "    idx_plot = (start < Xco2) & (Xco2 < stop)\n",
    "\n",
    "    f_mean, f_var = model.predict_f(Xplot, full_cov=False)\n",
    "    f_lower = f_mean - 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "    f_upper = f_mean + 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xco2[idx_plot], Yco2[idx_plot], \"kx\", mew=2)\n",
    "    (mean_line,) = ax.plot(Xplot, f_mean, \"-\")\n",
    "    color = mean_line.get_color()\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_lower, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_upper, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "    ax.fill_between(Xplot[:, 0], f_lower[:, 0], f_upper[:, 0], color=color, alpha=0.1)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "def plot_co2_kernel(\n",
    "    kernel: gpflow.kernels.Kernel,\n",
    "    mean_function: Optional[gpflow.functions.MeanFunction] = None,\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "        (Xco2, Yco2),\n",
    "        kernel=kernel,\n",
    "        mean_function=mean_function,\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "    opt.minimize(\n",
    "        model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables, options=dict(maxiter=10_000)\n",
    "    )\n",
    "    gpflow.utilities.print_summary(model, \"notebook\")\n",
    "\n",
    "    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2)\n",
    "    plot_co2_model_prediction(ax1, model, 1950, 2050)\n",
    "    plot_co2_model_prediction(ax2, model, 2015, 2030)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0e2de011",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us start by trying to fit our favourite kernel: the squared exponential:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "id": "65355caf",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {

     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:47.485835Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:47.485270Z"
    }
   },

    {

       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.lengthscales</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">   49.8908 </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.likelihood.variance</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus + Shift</td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    4.70003</td></tr>\n",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "69718cb1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We are off to a good start. From the left plot it is clear that the kernel has captured the long-term trend of the data. However, on the zoomed-in plot on the right it is also clear that the data has some kind of yearly cycle that our model has failed to capture.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us try adding a periodic kernel to capture the yearly cycle:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "id": "50d64722",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:47.487942Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:47.487757Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:35:56.160983Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:35:56.160405Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [

       "<thead>\n",

       "</thead>\n",
       "<tbody>\n",

       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[0].lengthscales            </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    nan</td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.variance    </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    nan</td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.lengthscales</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    nan</td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].period                  </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    nan</td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.likelihood.variance                       </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus + Shift</td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    nan</td></tr>\n",

   "source": [
    "plot_co2_kernel(\n",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "23e07667",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Huh. What happened? The optimiser has completely failed to find a good fit. With the extended model the loss function has become too complicated for the optimiser.\n",
    "\n",
    "Below we will look at what we can do to help the optimiser."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "783b3fc8",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Setting the initial value\n",
    "\n",
    "The simplest thing you can do to help the optimiser is to set your parameters to good inital values.\n",
    "\n",
    "* When we just fit a single `SquaredExponential` to the data we got great values for the long term trend. Let us reuse those parameters.\n",
    "* We know that we intend the periodic kernel to capture a yearly cycle. The units on the X-axis are years, so the period should be 1.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us try simply setting the parameters of our long-term-trend kernel to approximately those learned when it was trained individually, and the period to 1:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 18,
   "id": "1112f1fd",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:35:56.163223Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:35:56.163057Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.333185Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.332611Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<table>\n",
       "<thead>\n",
       "<tr><th>name                                          </th><th>class    </th><th>transform       </th><th>prior  </th><th>trainable  </th><th>shape  </th><th>dtype  </th><th style=\"text-align: right;\">       value</th></tr>\n",
       "</thead>\n",
       "<tbody>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[0].variance                </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">280000      </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[0].lengthscales            </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    15.619  </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.variance    </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">   198.385  </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.lengthscales</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">     1.86191</td></tr>\n",

       "<tr><td>GPR.likelihood.variance                       </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus + Shift</td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">     0.20905</td></tr>\n",

   "source": [
    "plot_co2_kernel(\n",
    "    gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential(variance=280_000, lengthscales=140.0)\n",
    "    + gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential(), period=1.0)\n",

   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c377f2f3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Priors\n",
    "\n",
    "It it always a good idea to try to set reasonable initial values on your parameters. However, it is not always enough. An initial value is just a starting point, and the optimiser may in principle choose any value whatsever for the final value. Another, possibly more principled, approach to guiding the optimiser is to set a \"prior\" on your parameters. A prior is a probability distribution that represents your belief of what the parameter should be, before the optimiser takes the data into account. We use the [TensorFlow Probability Distribution](https://www.tensorflow.org/probability/api_docs/python/tfp/distributions/Distribution) class to represent priors."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "93f0372d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "There are two ways to apply a prior to your parameters. First, you can create the parameter with the prior:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "id": "20f743e9",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.335455Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.335263Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.339807Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.339302Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "p = gpflow.Parameter(1.0, prior=tfp.distributions.Normal(loc=1.0, scale=10.0))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "74b3027a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Or you can create the parameter first, and then set the prior:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "id": "10c6afd0",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.341981Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.341786Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.345949Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.345410Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "p = gpflow.Parameter(1.0)\n",
    "p.prior = tfp.distributions.Normal(loc=1.0, scale=10.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "72e29142",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us try using priors on our $CO_2$ model:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "id": "ed9ab3c8",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.347982Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:36:05.347800Z",

    }

    {

       "</thead>\n",
       "<tbody>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[0].variance                </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>LogNormal</td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">262.867  </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[0].lengthscales            </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>LogNormal</td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">100.188  </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.variance    </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>         </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">319.79   </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.lengthscales</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>         </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\"> 19.7823 </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].period                  </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>LogNormal</td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">  1.00165</td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.likelihood.variance                       </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus + Shift</td><td>         </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">  5.54227</td></tr>\n",
       "</tbody>\n",

   "source": [
    "long_term_kernel = gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential()\n",
    "long_term_kernel.variance.prior = tfp.distributions.LogNormal(\n",
    "    tf.math.log(gpflow.utilities.to_default_float(280_000.0)), 1.0\n",
    ")\n",
    "long_term_kernel.lengthscales.prior = tfp.distributions.LogNormal(\n",
    "    tf.math.log(gpflow.utilities.to_default_float(140.0)), 0.1\n",
    ")\n",
    "periodic_kernel = gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential())\n",
    "periodic_kernel.period.prior = tfp.distributions.LogNormal(\n",
    "    tf.math.log(gpflow.utilities.to_default_float(1.0)), 0.1\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "plot_co2_kernel(long_term_kernel + periodic_kernel)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "095b5a4d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice that many parameters have constraints on what values are valid. In this case all of `variance`, `lengthscales` and `period` should be non-negative. That is why we chose the `LogNormal` distribution for our prior - it only allows positive values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "69c9b340",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Also notice in our table of parameters, that the `prior` column now shows `LogNormal` for the parameters we set the prior on."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "27b8a8ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Transforms\n",
    "\n",
    "As mentioned above, some parameters have constraints on what values are valid. GPflow uses \"transforms\" to enforce this. The parameter stores a raw value that can be anything. When you read the parameter that value is sent through a function, the \"transform\" that maps the entire real line to the set of valid values. We use the [TensorFlow Probability Bijector](https://www.tensorflow.org/probability/api_docs/python/tfp/bijectors/Bijector) class for the transform."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6f0dadd3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "You can only set the transform of a parameter when you create it. For example:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 22,
   "id": "b33984a4",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:36:08.222807Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:36:08.222650Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:08.226886Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:08.226516Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "p = gpflow.Parameter(1.0, transform=tfp.bijectors.Exp())"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "9a6b5ded",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this example we used the exponential function as a transform. Since the exponential functions maps the entire real line to positive values this transform will ensure that the parameter always take positive values."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b88a15f6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We can access the untransformed value of the parameter:"
   ]
  },

   "source": [

  {

   "metadata": {},

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d9e837ea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Again, be aware that many parameters have constraints on what kind of values they logically can take, and if you replace the transform of a parameter you must make sure that the transform only allows values that are logically valid in the context in which they are used.\n",
    "\n",
    "Also, notice how the values of the `transform` column in our parameter summary has updated to reflect our new transforms."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "053d05dc",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Trainable parameters\n",
    "\n",
    "In this section we have been going from setting initial parameter values, which are a very soft hint, over priors to transforms, which are more forceful ways of constraining the training process. The last step is to completely prevent the optimiser from changing a value. We can do that by setting the parameter to not be \"trainable\".\n",
    "\n",
    "You can set the trainability of a parameter either when you create it, or using the `gpflow.set_trainable` function:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "id": "df4ce575",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.078002Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.077849Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.081816Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.081313Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "p = gpflow.Parameter(1.0, trainable=False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,
   "id": "7eb86905",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.083600Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.083451Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.089908Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:16.089508Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "p = gpflow.Parameter(1.0)\n",
    "gpflow.set_trainable(p, False)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a4c69063",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The `gpflow.set_trainable` function can both be applied directly to parameters, or to modules, in which case all parameters held in the module are affected.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let us try setting the trainability on our $CO_2$ model:"
   ]
  },
  {

     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:18.687381Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:18.686922Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {

   "id": "8fdc2866",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Notice how the `trainable` column of the parameter table reflects the whether the parameters are trainable. Also notice how the final value of the un-trainable parameters have exactly the value we initialised them to. Setting a parameter untrainable is a heavy-handed tool, and we generally recommend using one of the softer methods demonstrated above."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e6191cd",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Advanced training"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "40e3fffa",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Multi-stage training\n",
    "\n",
    "Remember how we first trained a model with only a `SquaredExponential` kernel, and in the above subsections we have been using parameters learned from that experiment for the initial values in a more complicated kernel? Well, it is possible to run optimisation multiple times, so instead of \"copy and pasting\" values, we can learn them anew every time. This is mostly useful if your data might change, and you are trying to write solid reusable code:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 30,
   "id": "3fae00fd",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:36:18.689534Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:36:18.689350Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:36:26.536201Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:36:26.535693Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/html": [
       "<table>\n",
       "<thead>\n",
       "<tr><th>name                                          </th><th>class    </th><th>transform       </th><th>prior  </th><th>trainable  </th><th>shape  </th><th>dtype  </th><th style=\"text-align: right;\">      value</th></tr>\n",
       "</thead>\n",
       "<tbody>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[0].variance                </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>False      </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">99917.7    </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[0].lengthscales            </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>False      </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">   49.887  </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.variance    </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>False      </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    1      </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].base_kernel.lengthscales</td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>False      </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    1      </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.kernel.kernels[1].period                  </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus        </td><td>       </td><td>False      </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    1      </td></tr>\n",
       "<tr><td>GPR.likelihood.variance                       </td><td>Parameter</td><td>Softplus + Shift</td><td>       </td><td>True       </td><td>()     </td><td>float64</td><td style=\"text-align: right;\">    0.34501</td></tr>\n",

   "source": [
    "long_term_kernel = gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential()\n",
    "\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR((Xco2, Yco2), kernel=long_term_kernel)\n",
    "opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "opt.minimize(\n",
    "    model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables, options=dict(maxiter=10_000)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "periodic_kernel = gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential())\n",
    "\n",
    "kernel = long_term_kernel + periodic_kernel\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR((Xco2, Yco2), kernel=long_term_kernel)\n",
    "opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "opt.minimize(\n",
    "    model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables, options=dict(maxiter=10_000)\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "gpflow.set_trainable(kernel, False)\n",
    "plot_co2_kernel(kernel)"
   ]

   "source": [
    "### The Keras optimisers\n",
    "\n",
    "So far we have been using the optimiser from GPflow. However, GPflow is built on TensorFlow variables and automatic differentiation, and you can use any other optimiser built on those as well. Here is an example of using a Keras optimiser with a TensorFlow model:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 31,
   "id": "1d296720",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {

   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (Xco2, Yco2),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential(variance=280_000, lengthscales=140.0)\n",
    "    + gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.SquaredExponential(), period=1.0),\n",
    ")\n",
    "\n",
    "opt = tf.keras.optimizers.Adam()\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "@tf.function\n",
    "def step() -> tf.Tensor:\n",
    "    opt.minimize(model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "for i in range(2_000):\n",
    "    step()\n",
    "    if i % 100 == 0:\n",
    "        print(i, model.training_loss().numpy())\n",
    "\n",
    "kernel = model.kernel\n",
    "gpflow.set_trainable(kernel, False)\n",
    "plot_co2_kernel(kernel)"
   ]
  }
